revision.text:
The '''American Association of Teachers of French''' (AATF) is a professional organisation for teachers of [[French language|French]] in the United States founded in 1927. Teachers may be involved in primary, secondary, or university education. Additionally, retired and student teachers are welcome. Currently there are about 10,000 members.<ref>{{cite news|title=Convention annuelle de l'association américaine des professeurs de français à San Jose|url=http://www.france-amerique.com/articles/2009/07/01/convention_annuelle_de_l_association_americaine_des_professeurs_de_francais_a_san_jose.html|accessdate=27 December 2012|newspaper=France-Amérique|date=1 July 2009}}</ref> As the interest in French has declined in the United States since 1980's, the organisation has held annual convention to bring together a cross-section of teachers and educators to find ways to promote French in traditional curriculum and other methods.<ref>{{cite news|title=Teachers Try to Renew Interest in French|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/10/25/nyregion/teachers-try-to-renew-interest-in-french.html|accessdate=27 December 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 October 1998}}</ref>
The AATF's official publication is called ''The French Review'', which has the largest circulation of any scholarly journal on the French language.<ref>{{cite web|title=The FRENCH REVIEW|url=http://www.wwu.edu/depts/mcl/french/fr/|publisher=Western Washington University|accessdate=27 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117202627/http://www.wwu.edu/depts/mcl/french/FR/|archive-date=2012-11-17|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
==National French Contest== The '''National French Contest''' was established in 1936 by the Executive Council of AATF to help determine the relative student achievement in the learning of French in the United States. Originally the contest was called '''Le Grand Concours National de Français'''<ref>{{cite news|title=PMA students top in French contest|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=KFIQUvoPKFAC&dat=19820519&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|accessdate=27 December 2012|newspaper=Nashua Telegraph|date=19 May 1982|page=41}}</ref> but was later shortened to '''Le Grand Concours'''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=1936–2010: Le Grand Concurs Celebrates 75 Years|journal=National Bulletin|date=November 2009|volume=35|issue=2|pages=1|url=http://www.frenchteachers.org/bulletin/archives/2000s/2009-34.2nov.pdf|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref>
The annual contest currently has around 100,000 participants from elementary schools to high schools in all chapters nationwide. There are seven levels. The first level called FLES is for elementary school students. Levels 01, and 1 to 5 are for grades 7 to 12. In each level, there are divisions A to E to separate students based on prior exposure to French. About 0.1% of all participants receive gold medals for National Rank 1. About 0.7% receive silver medals for National Ranks 2 to 3. About 8% receive bronze medals for National Ranks 4 to 10.<ref>{{cite web|title=Le Grand Concours 2011 - Statistics |url=http://www.frenchteachers.org/concours/Resources/gc_stats.html |publisher=American Association of Teachers of French |accessdate=27 December 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617012133/http://www.frenchteachers.org/concours/Resources/gc_stats.html |archivedate=June 17, 2011 }}</ref>
==See also== *[[American Council on the Teaching of Foreign Languages]] *[[American Association of Teachers of German]]
