{{about||the village in Iran|Bejan, Iran|the Romanian village|Şoimuş|the mechanical engineer|Adrian Bejan}}
{{wiktionary}}
'''Bejan''' (Fr. ''bejaune'', from ''bec jaune'', "yellow beak," in allusion to unfledged birds, and the equivalent to Ger. ''Gelbschnabel'') was a term for [[First year|freshmen]], or [[Undergraduate education|undergraduates]] of the first year, in the [[Universities in Scotland#Middle Ages|Scottish universities]]. The term is rarely used today except at the [[University of Aberdeen]] Aberdeen; at the [[University of St Andrews]] the word has mutated to "Bejant" (female: Bejantine).

The phrase was introduced from the [[List of colleges and universities in France|French universities]], where the levying of ''bejaunium'' ("footing-money") had been prohibited by the statutes of the [[Orléans#University_and_other_education|university of Orleans]] in 1365 and by those of [[University of Toulouse|Toulouse]] in 1401. In 1493 the election of an ''Abbas Bejanorum'' (Abbot of the Freshmen) was forbidden in the [[university of Paris]].

