{{Multiple issues| {{globalize/US|date=March 2017}} {{refimprove|date=April 2017}} {{Orphan|date=April 2017}} }}
'''The Master of Science in [[Marketing]]''' (or '''MS Marketing''') is a [[graduate degree]] that prepares the student to work in [[middle-management]]-and-above marketing positions. The specific field within marketing will depend on the student, their program, and the firm with which they will work. Fields may include [[brand management]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rauschnabel|first=Philipp A.|last2=Krey|first2=Nina|last3=Babin|first3=Barry J.|last4=Ivens|first4=Bjoern S.|date=2016-08-01|title=Brand management in higher education: The University Brand Personality Scale|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0148296316000369|journal=Journal of Business Research|volume=69|issue=8|pages=3077–3086|doi=10.1016/j.jbusres.2016.01.023}}</ref> [[digital marketing]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wymbs|first=Cliff|year=2011|title=Digital Marketing: The Time for a New "Academic Major" Has Arrived|url=|journal=Journal of Marketing Education|volume=1–14|pages=14|via=}}</ref> integrated marketing communication,<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/036381119190020L?via=ihub|title=Integrated marketing communications: A new master's degree concept |language=en|access-date=2017-03-29|doi=10.1016/0363-8111(91)90020-L|volume=17|journal=Public Relations Review|pages=237–244 | last1 = Caywood | first1 = Clarke}}</ref> marketing [[analytics]] and [[research]], [[marketing strategy]], [[pricing strategy]] and many others.
The key difference between the MS Marketing degree and the [[Master of Business Administration]] (MBA) degree is the required number of marketing courses in the degree. Typically the MBA degree may have a concentration in marketing or other fields of 4-6 courses. The MS Marketing degree will usually have 10-12 marketing courses. The MBA will offer courses in [[accounting]], [[finance]], [[business]] strategy, marketing, organizational behavior and other general business courses in much less depth than a specialized degree<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Laud|first=Robert L.|last2=Johnson|first2=Matthew S.|date=2013-03-01|title=Progress and Regress in the MBA Curriculum: The Career and Practice Skills Gap|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/15416518.2013.781398|journal=Organization Management Journal|volume=10|issue=1|pages=24–35|doi=10.1080/15416518.2013.781398}}</ref> such as the MS Marketing degree that requires marketing courses, supplemented with perhaps a few [[electives]] in other areas such as analytics.
