{{unreferenced|date=November 2017}}
{{notability|date=November 2017}}

'''Simulated Society''' (or '''SimSoc''', pronounced sim-sock) is a "[[Simulation game|game]]" used by [[university|universities]] and other groups to teach various aspects of [[sociology]], [[political science]], and [[communications]] skills.  Originally created by [[William A. Gamson]] in 1966, it is currently in its fifth edition.  It provides a way for participants to better understand the problems of [[governance|governing]] a 20th-century-style [[nation state]] society. The participants grapple with issues like [[economic inequality]], [[justice]], [[Diversity (politics)|diversity]], [[Trust (social sciences)|trust]], [[Power (philosophy)|power dynamics]], and [[leadership]] as they negotiate their way through [[Labour economics|labor]]-[[management]] [[Labor relations|relations]], [[politics|political turmoil]], and [[natural disasters]]. To be successful, players must utilize basic [[Social control|social process]]es from [[cooperation]] and [[Reward (psychology)|reward]] to [[threat]] and [[punishment]]. The goal of SIMSOC is to bring a deeper understanding to everyday experiences as well as [[social theory|social]] and [[organizational theory]].


